<br>
I see there are quiet a few RP guilds here on this server, and so I am seriously considering starting a new character HERE.<br>
<br>
Below, I give you a challenge, perhaps a diversion....do you have time to sit and drink a mug of gnomish java and enjoy a prelude to a story I wish to weave upon Norrath?  Do you have the power of the mightiest weapon, the quill and ink, to play your parts?  If so, I may have found a home on Brell, and perhaps a home in a guild if my story catches your interest, for I only write the prelude and the view of my character....the other views are up to YOU to write.<br>
<br>
So sit down with a mug or an ale, and welcome to the POLITICS OF ELVES<br>
<br>
This first post is quite long, it is the backdrop of a my character and how she fits into Norrath.....and as you will see at the end of this post, once you have the prelude read, you are all invited to do YOUR part in writing this story. Do not rush into reading this, wait until you have the time to enjoy a cup of java and settle into this book that we can all write together.<br>
<br>
~~~~~~***~~~~~<br>
<br>
The Politics of Elves<br>
Part One<br>
<br>
<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
***The characters that support the following story are ACTUAL npc's you will find in Norrath with the exception of:<br>
Miaza, the midwife cleric<br>
Wardrym the boy that was switched at birth<br>
Saffryn the girl that was switched at birth<br>
Saffryn's parents, Safyre Heartwood-Trueshot and Frynn Trueshot.<br>
!~~~~~~~~~*********~~~~~~~~~<br>
~~~~~~~~~**********~~~~~~~~~~<br>
<br>
<br>
Chapter One: The Present<br>
<br>
JOURNAL:<br>
<br>
I am the fifth child and only daughter of Safyre Hearthwood, my mother, and Frynn Trueshot, my father. My family stretches out with cousins, aunts and uncles, blood related and married. My eldest brother, Maesyn is the guild master since my father's retirement from the ranger's guild, Champions of Faydark. Ran Sunfire is my cousin as is the prankster of our family, Dill Fireshine, so naturally, I was sent to the guild of rangers to train like my father and brothers before me.<br>
<br>
Other family of note are my jolly aunt and uncle, Uuilanu and Manlawen Hearthwood, owners of the Hearthwood Tavern. <br>
<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
Insert of Miaza Goldsinger<br>
<br>
Twenty-one years in the Past....<br>
<br>
I am a cleric of the Koada'Dal, and midwife to many of the women of Felwithe, and all is not well in the Great House of Nobleheart. So much unrest. The Koada'Dal dictate from our lofty towers to the Baronry's of the Feir'Dal, the earthier of our kind and more at touch with the common folk. <br>
<br>
From these palace walls the Princes cannot see and do not care for the lives that produce their daily comforts, only for what they are rightfully due by birth as High-Elves.<br>
<br>
And it is a birth that destroys this great house. M'lady Niola has given birth to her second lifeless child, another girl. The Prince is livid. Our Lord is the Prince of Paladins, Joren Nobleheart. I feel for his poor wife, for she is not the first Lady Nobleheart in mortal danger, but the third.<br>
<br>
A once young Prince had married his first wife, producing three lifeless daughters. She mysteriously died shortly after the last stillborn infant. The midwife disappeared.<br>
<br>
I became the family midwife to the second Lady Nobleheart, being sent by my brother, Kitool Goldsinger. At the birth of the Lady's first child, a girl, there was much hope, but alas, the child lasted but two weeks and failed to thrive. She bore the Prince's heirs five more times, unheard of for a Koada'Dal, but each daughter lived less time than the one before and after much fighting and verbal abuse from the Prince and leader of our Paladin forces, the second Lady Nobleheart was found dead at the base of the stairs, the bruises and broken neck attributed to her fall. But I knew better.<br>
<br>
Another round of celebration and the Prince Joren marries again. This time to a magician-trained lass, Niola Impholder. She is not the average Koada'Dal. She has dark hair, and bears &quot;the taint of wood-elf&quot; as the Prince calls it, but it is the secret hope this will make her stronger at bearing healthy children, as the Fier'Dal are masters of proliferation.<br>
<br>
Niola bears her first, a girl, that lives amazingly one month. On the eve before the child is to be declared legal Heir to the Nobleheart House, she dies peacefully in her sleep, as though she simply forgot to breathe. A second child is born, the Prince's eleventh child, all accursed girls, and too, quickly dies. In a fit of rage, the Prince of Paladins nearly beats his poor wife to death and storms off to the clerics guild to grab his cousin, Terren Starwatcher, for a night of drinking and wenching. <br>
<br>
And I make my plans... <br>
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<br>
Re: Insert of Miaza Goldsinger, Part II, Twenty years in the Past<br>
<br>
It is a year later and m'Lady Niola Impholder-Nobleheart has passed the half-way mark of her pregnancy. I make a bold demand and stand toe-to-toe with the Prince, secretly quaking in my soft boots. But to my surprise, Prince Nobleheart agrees. Let the Lady Niola finish her internment at his private hunting lodge in quiet peace. Healthy air and lack of duties can only help the child within the mother grow stronger. He shrugs and proclaims it done, and so off we take ourselves to where I can complete, Tunare willing, my plan.<br>
<br>
~~~~~~~~~~~~*****~~~~~~~~~~~~<br>
<br>
From the lodge it is not far to the Tree City of happy, bustily productive Fier'Dal. The Barons oversee all the hunting and growing of food, making our spirits and ales, and our weapons ready for enchanting by our Enchanters at the Palace. The Princes and Princesses of the Koada'Dal do not appreciate the work nor the importance the wood-elf Barons have upon their lives, caring only that they are given what they haughtily believe they are due.<br>
<br>
More importantly to m'Lady's life is one particular Fier'Dal, the pregnant Lady Trueshot, pregnant with her fifth healthy babe, a lusty boy no doubt. The Lady Safyre Heartwood-Trueshot and her husband, Baron Frynn Trueshot are the heads of two powerful families among the Feir'dal. But the timing is right, and so for m'lady's sake....<br>
<br>
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~*******~~~~~~~~~~~~<br>
<br>
I dreamed last night of the coming deed. If I fail, I surely will die, but then so shall m'lady when the child she carries dies. <br>
<br>
But this is a dream, and all is well in dreams, and here in that comfort my plans unfolded nicely. At the onset of m'lady's labor, I hurridly made a quick social visit to the Lady Trueshot, checking on her pregnancy due to labor in a moon's time. Secretly I slipped belladonna leaves into her tea to start her labor early. May Tunare forgive me.<br>
<br>
Rushing back to m'lady Niola, I helped her give birth to a silent, but breathing daughter, blond curls mashed to her wet skin looking very much like her father with his high cheekbones. I set the lady to sleep after the birthing, and placed the quiet baby girl into my basket and covered her with clean towels. By now the runner had arrived to alert me to the Lady Trueshots labors and that they were ready for me to attend to her birth. A dark hair boy was born, a bit small in his prematurity, but lustily screaming all the same. I keep him from his mother's vision with excuses of cleaning &quot;her&quot; up and once he quieted down, I placed the quiet baby girl in her arms and slipped the boy infant into the basket, covering him with towels. Quickly excusing myself, I left with the prize healthy child and a last look at the little pink girl that was now being cooed over by an unsuspecting father. Soon, I returned to my Lady Niola to place the child within her arms. She knew not where this child came from, but she was greatful of it, and at first sight fell in love with this child as though he were her own.<br>
<br>
As for the Trueshots, they have four healthy boys. When this, no-doubt sickly baby girl dies, it will not shatter their world. Life will move on. And in turn, the House Nobleheart now has an Heir, and all will be at peace. <br>
<br>
<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
Chapter Two<br>
<br>
Twenty years after the actions of Miaza, we are back in the Present:<br>
<br>
Wardrym Nobleheart watches the dinner his father holds for all the Princes of Felwithe. Their excesses are vulgar and overwhelming in their haughtery and debauchery. Lightening strikes and heralds the approach of a violent storm outside the palace and his father, Prince Joren, turns to his son, &quot;Go boy, and take your mother's hand. You know how storms send her into one of her sicknesses&quot;. The Princes all snicker at their host's words.<br>
<br>
Wardrym reddens in anger and stalks away to his mother's chambers.<br>
<br>
&quot;How is she, Miaza?&quot;<br>
&quot;She is tired, but well enough. Go on in lad. She has been asking for you.&quot;<br>
<br>
The young man is dark haired like his mother, shorter than the average high-elf, but broad shouldered non the less. He enters his mother's inner chambers and sits on her bed and gently takes her hand as the storm outside reaches a cresendo.<br>
<br>
She turns and smiles at him. &quot;Such a terrible storm,&quot; she sighs. &quot;Much like the night you came to me.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Yes mother, I know, it stormed the night I was born at the hunting lodge&quot;.<br>
<br>
&quot;I've never really known where you were born, but it was that very night you came to me. I have loved you as my own child from that horrible, horrible night.&quot;<br>
<br>
Wardrym's eyes narrow, &quot;but I am your own child, mother, I am dark haired like you,&quot;<br>
<br>
Lady Niola looks straight at Wardrym through unclear eyes as though looking through him and interrupts, &quot;Nay son, I sufferred greatly that night, birthing yet another of Joren's cursed female babies, born quiet and pink and doomed. Miaza saved my life that night, she took that wretched child away and gave me you, didn't you Miaza?&quot;<br>
<br>
Wardrym turns to see Miaza has silently entered the room, a look of shock upon her face. A mix of emotions quickly pass across her face from fear to guilt, and she quickly looks to her feet, speaking softly, &quot;Prince Joren must never know, m'lord, but 'tis true. Your mother, m'lady Niola would no doubt have died for the birthing of that baby. You were her only hope for life and the only hope for peace within the House of Nobleheart.&quot;<br>
<br>
Nobleheart begins to pace the room, looking to his mother peacefully unaware of his turmoil while she lives in her state of reccurring dementia. He looks to his family's healer, Miaza who has been faithful above all others to his family's house for as long as he can remember, always a staunch protector of his mother.<br>
<br>
A thought and he turns to Miaza, &quot;The girl child, what became of her?&quot;<br>
<br>
Miaza begins her tale of that horrible night, true to the dream she had once had but for two things...in reality, there was a horrible storm...and in reality, the girl child lived.<br>
<br>
&quot;And so you are telling me, Miaza, that this girl child that lives is the true heir to this House of debauchery, and I am but a wood-elf imposter?&quot;<br>
<br>
Quietly, still looking at the toes of her boots, &quot;yes m'lord.&quot;<br>
<br>
Incredulously, he begins to laugh, &quot;And what has become of this girl?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Of that I do not know m'lord. No doubt she is happy and surrounded by many brothers&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Oh no doubt, brothers that would be mine. Is she in a good house at least?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Oh yes, my lord, her family's house is well thought of among the Feir'dal.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;The Feir'dal...I am a Feir'dal,&quot; Wardrym shakes his head and sighs.<br>
<br>
Miaza looks up to the young Prince pleading, &quot;Please m'lord, do not tell this secret. Your father would not accept this girl as his Heir, and he would kill you for not being his blood-son, he'd kill your mother for the betrayal even though this is all my doing. Please, please m'lord, you MUST keep this secret.&quot;<br>
<br>
Looking thoughtfully, playing with his bottom lip, Wardrym slowly nods his head, &quot;Yes, yes I can see the need to keep this secret.&quot; He makes descision. &quot;I am going to make a trip to the hunting lodge. Don't worry Miaza. I will keep all secrets. But for my own peace of mind, I must find answers to the pile of questions haunting me.&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
Chapter Three<br>
<br>
Journal of Saffryn:<br>
<br>
Master Hearthwood has promised me that upon reaching my 9th Season, I would be allowed to travel to Freeport with one of the Druid accolytes to obtain my firebeetle eye for my Flame-Lick spell. My cousin Drynil, a druid in training, and I have been making excited plans.<br>
<br>
Spells and more spells...I feel all this magical energy within me and I know I am stronger than some of the other students, but CHANNELING it from a ball of emotional energy to a pinpoint of purposeful direction is so HARD. Whenever I see an orc I just want to fillet him with my sword. Master says that is fine for emotional children, but I must learn control and refine my battle skills and start making use of the magic that Tunare saw fit to give us…..I'd still rather fillet the orc.<br>
<br>
~~~~~~~~~~~~~***********~~~~~~~~~~~<br>
<br>
I reached my 9th Season this night. Tomorrow Drynil and I begin our adventure to Freeport.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
&quot;Have you enough food and water?&quot; asks a tallish blond half-elf.<br>
&quot;Yes mother,&quot; Saffryn replies with a sigh. &quot;You needn't toddle after me mother, I'm a big girl&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;A bit tall for your age, but only 20 none the less, and that's very young for an elven young lady&quot; Safyre replies.<br>
<br>
The dark haired Frynn enters his daughter's room and interrupts, &quot;Ladies, ladies. You bicker like, like, well, like mother and daughter.&quot;<br>
<br>
Both Safyre and Saffryn turn to the male intruder, each raising one elegant brow.<br>
<br>
&quot;Alright, alright, I'm leaving. I just wanted to wish you luck my little one.&quot; Frynn replies as he reaches up to kiss his daughter on the forehead, as she is equal his height. &quot;How you got so tall I'll never know, no doubt comes from your mother's mother being human.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;No doubt from you giving me all sons first and she had to reach their height just to survive the wrestling over toys,&quot; shoots back Safyre playfully. &quot;Now go, we women are busy.&quot;<br>
<br>
~~~~~~~~*****~~~~~~<br>
<br>
Chapter Four<br>
<br>
Hunting Lodge <br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
After hours of arguing with logics and reason with his father, Wardrym finally strikes upon a chord that makes his father relent. He demands that his father give him the family's hunting lodge, Willowswood, as his own for he shall never find decent women within the palace to wench as long as his father is taking the cream of the crop. Prince Joren stops short, throws his head back in a hearty laugh, and calls for his Counsiliary to bring forth the Deed and Title to the hunting lodge, and promptly signs it over to Wardrym.<br>
~~~~~~***~~~~~~<br>
<br>
Wardrym has spent most of a week helping set Willowswood to rights, its wild beauty hidden in years of dust and neglect. He works side by side with his servants, but that is not strange to them. Even as a boy, they knew Wardrym was not the typical high-elf, always caring about them, defending their children as he would defend his own brothers had he any siblings.<br>
<br>
Once the manor is in order, he keeps himself in the garments of the common folk around them, finding the leggings of the wood-elves more comfortable than the fancy robes his family wears. <br>
<br>
He finds he can travel freely about in Greater Faydark, from the Lodge all the way to Kelethin...no constant bowing and insincere compliments, no constant bending of his ear to secure favor through him to his father. Wardrym finds a freedom he never knew he missed, even enjoying sleeping under the stars and the canopy of age-old trees. <br>
<br>
Miaza had confessed to Wardrym the name of his true family and he has spent much time learning of them. He finds that his blood-father, dark haired like himself, is a much respected Baron and retired head of the ranger guild, that his eldest brother is master there now. He learns of the success of the three other brothers. His birth-mother has fair hair, born the third child to the brother of the Fier'Dal Baron Hearthwood and a human mother. That explains his towering over most the wood-elves he comes across, and then again, why he was shorter than most men in the Felwithe Palace, he muses. But then he had gotten used to his friends calling him &quot;Runt&quot;. <br>
<br>
And then there is the girl. Aye, he thinks to himself, she is much like the Prince, perhaps without the mean-streak, but then again... While watching the girl train from afar, he could not help but catch that extra blow to her opponant's back with the flat side of her sword, AFTER the duel was called over. With a critical eye he imagines her blond hair in a high ponytail, exposing those high cheekbones hidden by layers of that tangled mess. She is equal in height of most the young men she trains in, taller then most the women. Long legged, and a bit clumsly, she unknowingly is the cause of many a chuckle from Wardrym.<br>
<br>
<br>
And more and more the thought crosses the mind of Wardrym...how can I put this aright? <br>
<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
Chapter Five<br>
<br>
Hugging all their brothers and cousins, and their mothers and fathers at the platform above the lift, Saffryn Trueshot and Drynil Heartwood step onto the lift and wave farewell to their family as it begins to lower to the ground.<br>
<br>
Stepping off at the bottom, they dutifully report to Guard Pineshade. Then they heft their packs to their backs, cracked staff in Drynil's hand, a tarnished sword in the hand of Saffryn; they are ready for adventure. Drynil casts camoflage upon them and then starting with a skip, they begin their run to Butcherblock Mountains.<br>
<br>
<br>
The Chase<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
Having come from the Hearthwood tavern after a delightfull and animated discussion with its owners over a late breakfast, Ward, as his new Feir'Dal friends called him, was stunned as he turned onto the platform attached to the lift to see the entire Houses of Trueshot and Hearthwood standing there.<br>
<br>
&quot;Now you can't be too cautious Dryn, you keep that camoflauge up all the way to the Butcherblock docks, there are aqua goblins roaming about there.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Yes mother, of course. I'm not a brownie scout, I can handle this,&quot; replies Drynil.<br>
<br>
&quot;Well speaking of brownie scouts,&quot; pipes in Maesyn giving Saffryn a stern look, &quot;Don't be taken unawares...And for Tunare's sake, stick to the paths.<br>
<br>
Giving her father a pleading look, &quot;Da', tell them I'll be fine, I've traveled to Kaladim already once to turn in those belts to into Master Canloe, it's not much farther to the docks&quot;<br>
<br>
As the good-byes linger, Wardrum races for the next lift over and runs a shortcut through the woods to his Lodge. <br>
<br>
Reaching his new home, he leaps over a bramble bush, ducks under a low-hanging branch, and skids into the front hall. Out of breath he yells for Daina, the cook, for water and rations and takes the stairs to his chambers three at a time. Grabbing an empty pack from a hook in his room he stuffs it with a handful of small bottles containing invisibility-potions , a money purse, and then treds down the stairs again like thunder, grabs the supplies from Daina waiting in the hall and kisses her cheek as he flies out the door.<br>
<br>
Running the quick jaunt to the Wizard Spires, he stops dead center, bends over, grabbing his knees gasping for breath. <br>
<br>
A curious old gnomish wizard asks, &quot;Is there anything I can do for you lad?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;You haven't seen a tall blond wood-elf pass this way with a little dark druid one have you?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;You mean like the ones running this way?&quot; <br>
<br>
