Saffryn's Journal<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
Saturday, February 7th, 3178<br>
<br>
I thought the good-byes would never end. It's not like I'm running off to marry a troll...hmm ogres. Maybe Drynil should be sure to keep the camoflauge up after Two-Houses. Rumors say an overly made-up ogress is looking for her errant husband or such. Well, come on feet, let's run.<br>
<br>
~~~~~~~*********~~~~~~~<br>
<br>
My trip is cursed. I hate being a good-girl. I stuck to the path. Drynil kept our camo up, and what did it get me? My camo dropped just as I was nearing the Wizzy Spires where some deranged elf hooked on us like a tick. There we were, running along minding our own business and there stands talking to a gnome in a dress one dark haired mad-man with brambles stuck to his leggings and twigs in his hair, panting and sweating like an orc, gasping &quot;Hail&quot;..... the dweeb.<br>
<br>
Too bad he caught his second wind because next thing I know, he's running behind us. Drynil swears she doesn't know him, and I swore to her I don't often talk to crazy-running bushes. So I stopped and she camoed us we and continued on our way. We had thought we had lost him. <br>
<br>
Beautiful Butcherblock opened up into clear blue skies and the greenest of fields. Past goblins we ran, staying true to the path as I promised my Ma, twisting and turning through the dwarvish lands. I remembered the turn at the crossroads, heeded the warning of bandits, and turned the final pass to Kaladim, and what do I see but HIM. Sir Bramblepants. Arms flailing in the air like a Krag chick. And then he dissapears. Didn't look like any camo I'd ever seen. <br>
<br>
We stopped at Kaladim a bit to pretend to admire the huge statue of the dwarf at the entrance. Why did they make a statue of a short man so tall? Bet the Highty-Hauty Elfs would say its a short-man syndrome or something else as fancy. Anyway, was but an excuse to perk up our ears and listen for Bramblepants. Finally, at hearing nothing we couldn't give reason to, we continued on our way.<br>
<br>
At the dock we met a dwarf named Loanr. We didn't have much to say. I'm not a talky person anyway and it was getting late in the day. When the boat finally arrived, We got on with Loanr, a gnome who had joined us named Baldaran, and a dwarvish woman by the name of MissMedic who was to be my saviour later.<br>
<br>
It's not easy to keep your spells up on a rocking boat, and Sir Bramblepants appeared eventually looking a bit green. But he kept his distance at least. A wise choice on his part for near sunset a horrible storm began to toss the Siren's Bane about the sea like a feather in the wind and it was my turn to be more than green. I don't know what Sir Bramblepants was doing, but I was wretching myself inside out. That was when MissMedic came to my rescue. She handed me something she called a &quot;pill&quot;, no doubt a gnomish invention. She said it was an herb that had been dried and crushed and then formed into this perfect tiny pebble shape. It's a wonder I kept it down, but I did, and soon felt better for it. Drynil, of course, stayed at the bar down in the hold.<br>
<br>
Don't know what became of Sir Bramblepants, but I am settling down for the night at an inn called The Jade Tiger where I sit writing now. Drynil is at a party in the bar downstairs.   Maesyn would be blue in the face knowing I'm not camping under stars. He can sleep in the wild natural all he pleases, but this ranger is sleeping in a soft bed, thank you very much. <br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
Sunday, February 8th, 3178<br>
<br>
We awaken to a bright sunny day in a new city, Freeport. As to be expected, I had hoped it would be more than it is, but then I was warned. The streets are full of dirt, beggars here and there. I rounded a corner near some theater and almost stepped into a pile of dung. Had to be ogre. <br>
<br>
Well, I had a task at hand, bring back a pack full of fire-beetle eyes. We set out of the gate, boldly not even asking about for my soul to be bound here. Gah! The rats! What a filthy place. I was a bit surprised at the wealth flaunted by the orcs here, wearing garishly golden sashes yet carrying no more than a few coppers on them. Okay, so I didn't stick to just a few fire-beetles in my hunt. In fact, I was just picking over the body of the last orc I dropped when out of the corner of my eye, there's Sir Bramblepants flailing behind a cactus. Like no one is going to see those sparks going off. Almost looked like he set it afire before he dissappeared. <br>
<br>
Drynil gave him a dirty look and camoed us as we ran onward to East Commonlands to get out of the dust and dirt...and farther away from well, you know.<br>
<br>
Finally, grass and trees. I almost felt at home until I saw the tall human woman killing all those wolves and bears. Those poor animals. Worse yet, she just left their bodies. I understand killing an animal if there be reason, food, pelt for clothing, but this, this was sheer pleasure in killing innocent animals for fun and leaving the bodies to rot. On the brighter side, I was able to help a poor gnome, Stuta by name, who was being attacked by fire-beetle and skeleton at once. Makes one feel good for helping, it does. But good people here are few are far between. Drynil has been here before, so it was all old news to her. She just stayed near an inn drinking ale after I promised I wouldn't tell her Dah and sunned herself all day.<br>
<br>
I do not like this place.<br>
<br>
Lightened a skeleton of his bastard sword to complete my quest for Master Hearthwood. Got my pack full of fire-beetle eyes to pass out in Kelethin tomorrow, and got my fill of being followed by Sir Bramblepants playing hide-and seek with me.<br>
<br>
Finished with my task, Drynil delivered a sack of mail from Idia back home to Ton Twostring here in the Freeport Bard Guild, we walked out onto the street to see Sir Bramblepants begin his arm swinging again, as Drynil swung her own and promptly gated us home.<br>
<br>
I'm not sure, but I think I heard him say something as we gated. Sounded like &quot;I forgot they could do that.&quot;<br>
<br>
