Council of Barons<br>
~~~~~~~*********~~~~~~~<br>
<br>
Smoke curled from a rosewood pipe in a slender serpentine thread up to a small storm that was gathering above the heads of the Barons; and though the scent of the Hearthwood Tavern, with its pipes and ales and gathered kin was pleasant, the mood was tense. <br>
<br>
&quot;It's got to STOP!&quot; yelled Baron Ashwood, pounding a fist on the bar. &quot;We all know very well the raise in taxes is to line the Princes' pockets. We've all been into Crushbone, and if anything, their forces are weakening.&quot;<br>
<br>
Baron Trueheart taps his rosewood pipe into the ashtray and quietly replies, &quot;True enough, Learle, but everytime we stand against the Princes, they throw the Book of Laws at us. It's not this single act that is the trouble, tis the Book of Law itself.&quot;<br>
<br>
Looking around the room, Baron Webdancer and Baroness Windlehands of the Bards' Guild are nodding their heads in agreement, as well as Barons Tylfon and Expin of the Scouts.<br>
<br>
Baroness Kweili of the Gem Merchants stands, &quot;But what are we to do of it? The Book of Law has been in place since it was handed down by Tunare to our ancesters when we left Antonica for this land we hold now.&quot; <br>
<br>
Kweili sits as Baron Tilluen stands, also a Merchant Baron, &quot;And so how do we go against the Book of Law and the will of Tunare?&quot;<br>
<br>
Baron Regren takes his turn and answers, &quot;Is it Tunare's will for the so-called High Elves to hold to the letter of the law when the letter is of an ancient alphabet and Tunare's children have matured beyond its intent?&quot;<br>
<br>
Saffryn sits quietly, observing from her corner, smirking at the fletching merchant, Lord Lanin. &quot;He's found a solution to the raise in taxes, the crook,&quot; thinks Saffy, &quot;he's raised his prices much higher than the fletcher in the the shop near him. Beware the unwary.&quot;<br>
<br>
Baron Regen takes the attention of the floor again, &quot;Then the problem to solve is how do we break the Book of Law. The Princes hide behind the ancient rules to maintain their way of life. They will not let go of it easily.&quot;<br>
<br>
The argument continues long into the night. <br>
