<br>
&quot;We had two main families of elves, though we all looked much alike, and we all learned whatever profession we cared to learn. We were separated only by the name of our ancestral house,s whether we were of the House of Koad'dal, or the House of Feir'dal.&quot;<br>
<br>
First the House of Fier'Dal who lived in the forests gradually started crowding into the city, the waters dried, the food shortages began starving us out...we could not continue to exist, nor could we take lands from those already established.  Tunare said it would be wrong of us, that there was a gentler way.  Finally, our Goddess and Protector told the clerics that through them, she would lead us to a new world, but once we got there, we would have to be organized quickly to survive, there would be little room for mistakes to set up our home, for though there was space enough for all of us in the New World, there were others that would covet it.&quot;<br>
<br>
Daina wets her throat with the tea, then looks deep into the cream swirling there in her cup as she continues, &quot;Tunare handed down a directive to the Clerics, a Tome of instructions that, if followed to the letter, would save us.  Great boats were built to carry us, along with seeds of all kinds, plants to start anew, and animals for stock and breeding in the new world.  The preparations were made, and Tunare had handed down her instructions. She wanted us to &quot;specialize&quot;, not wasting resources in duplication, we would each be productive in what we do best.  No longer were the elves allowed to learn what struck their fancy.    The Fier'Dal were to no longer study arcane magics, as they were so intuned with nature, where the Koada'Dal were out of step with the cycles of nature, but were stronger in the ethereal elements.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;The boat trip was uneventful, though many were sick, unused to sea-travel, but once set upon the dry lands again, the trackers set forth ahead and blazed their way forward, warriors set to guard the perimeters of our large band of people, druids and clerics ready to heal, magical casters protected in the center ready to strengthen us. Immediately upon striking our claim upon the New World, we were to set those Fier'Dal to work building their tree houses and setting up perimeters of safety.  Koada-Dal no longer were to train as warriors save for those with some clerical ability to serve as Tunare's Holy Paladins.  Most were set to use their strength in magic to enchant magical weapons, to pray and heal, to stir up the ethereal to protect, while those woodies tracked, and built and worked with their hands.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Once the food was set to growth with the aid of the druids to set the plants healthy and strong, and the animals were set to the cycle of life in mating and birthing and growning anew, all elves were turned to set up the stronghold where the ethereal would be protected, the castle of Felwithe.  The Woodies, again, worked with their hands and practical magics, while those who studied High-Magic, those who would later be called the High-Elves, used their magics to move heavy blocks and magically seal outer walls and such.  They even magically protected their water source, that it would never dry up again, that the fish would be plentiful, that Tunare's people would ever be at home in their new land&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;And so, that has how it has been ever since. Those who had the strength of the land and practical magics lived with the land, and bred more of those strengths, druids, rangers, warriors, and bards. They began to carry a darker hue to their skin, a woodier color.  Those that specialized in the High-magics, the ethereal, became known as the High-Elves and grew paler in color living away from nature.  The drift between the two becoming wider and wider.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Since that time, the wood-elves have provided for all the elves, wood and high elven alike, with the rewards and fruits of the land.  High-elves have provided the intelligence and protection that high-magics and enchantments can provide. So set forth by Tunare, so is the Book of Law.&quot;<br>
<br>
