 Back to Wardrym:<br>
---------<br>
<br>
On the jog from Willowswood to Felwithe, Ward thinks on what he has learned and realizes that the only way to straighten out this mess is to start from the beginning, which means taking a good look at the original Book of Law. So far all he's seen are copies, and everyone he has talked to has also only seen copies. So, with that, he has decided to take up his study at the Castle and get a look at the original.<br>
<br>
Checking in at his father's home and dropping off a bag in his old room, Wardrym heads straight for the Paladin's guild to speak with an old friend.<br>
<br>
&quot;Seleni! How are you m'lady,&quot; Wardrym smiles winningly at Seleni Treekeeper.<br>
<br>
&quot;Now Wardrym Nobleheart, you've been away too long to start flirting at me with that smile of yours, what do you want.&quot; she replies with an air of suspicion at her old sparinng partner. &quot;You certainly aren't back to practice your riposte.&quot;<br>
<br>
Ward looks down at his toes guiltily, &quot;No, no, I'm not.&quot; he answers, then looking straight at her, &quot;I need your help, Seleni. It should be a simple matter. All I want is to look at the Book of Law, THE Book of Law. Problem is that I don't know where it is.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;You mean you father never told you? You being the heir of the Star of Felwithe?&quot; she looks incrediously at him.<br>
<br>
Trying not to look stupid he answers, &quot;Well, um, actually.....what is the Star of Felwithe&quot;.<br>
<br>
Chuckling at her old paladin classmate, Seleni pats him on the back, &quot;Come Wardrym, let's have a bit of wine and cheese and I'll fill you in on what that drunken father of yours has neglected to tell the next Prince of Paladins.&quot;<br>
<br>
They walk from the Paladin's guild and find a quiet corner booth where they can talk freely. After ordering a bottle of elven wine and a chunk of halvarti and a small loaf of sour bread, they resume their conversation.<br>
<br>
&quot;Now, Wardrym, you know of the Book of Law, that if was written and carried here all the way from Old Tunaria, yes?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Yes, and I know the story of the Exodus, and the rules that followed, all have seen a copy of it. What I want is to see the original.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Well, m'lord heir of Nobleheart, the original is locked away in the High Keep of Felwithe, protected by Wizard Lock, a spell cast by the direct ancestor of Tarker Blazetoss, the Master of the wizard guild now. The heads of each guild upon landing here in the New Land, Faydwer, not trusting each other, demanded that the lock-spell include a member of each of their guilds as a key. The warrior's cared not for such things that included magic and excluded themselves. That left five guild leaders, five points to a Star Council...Wizard, Mage, Enchanters, Paladins and Clerics.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Ah....the Star COUNCIL, I know of the Star Council, but know nothing of their involvement with the Book of Law, only that they hold the most weight in Parliment,&quot; offers Wardrym.<br>
<br>
&quot;Yes, Ward darling, now don't interrupt.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Sorry.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Where was I , oh yes. The legend says it was a dark and stormy night when the deed was done. Personally, I think that was just for effect to scare small children,&quot; Seleni says wryly. &quot;Whatever the weather, the Star Council, or the Star of Felwithe as it was called then , all five of them, met at the highest tower of Felwithe High-Keep. There they entered a room where upon the floor was and is tiled with a great five-pointed star. Each guild leader stood at a point of that star and the Book of Law rested upon a pedestal in the very center of the star. &quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;No one knows what spell was used, what components were needed, what words were spoken. Nevertheless, the outcome is for sure....no one can go near that book unless they are a direct descendent and heir of that Star Council. One can enter the room if they've permission or special clearance, but to step upon any part of that star means instant evaporation of your body fluids. A little messy in my opinion, but it was a MAN afterall that created the spell. Just a pile of bone and dried up sinew is all that's left.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I don't suppose &quot;Wow&quot; would be a very princely word right now,&quot; says Ward.<br>
<br>
&quot;Wow indeed.&quot; replies Seleni.<br>
<br>
&quot;One more question, Seleni and then I'm going to take you out for a night of dancing. Who are the members of the Star Council now?&quot;<br>
<br>
The tall red-head slaps Wardrym hard on the arm with her fan, &quot;Why Wardrym Nobleheart, your own father is ON that Star Council, you are HEIR to that council and are to replace him at his death, and you know NOTHING of our politics, who your oppononts will be...&quot; she replies aghast, mouth open in astonishment.<br>
<br>
Shaking her head she contines, &quot;Well keep this in your head Lord Nobleheart, next Prince of Paladins, those who will oppose you in council are as follows: Yeolarn Bronzeleaf and his daughter of the Clerics; Tarker Blazetoss and his daughter, Serri Moonwatcher (of whom you used to date, you goose) of the Wizards; your mother's cousin Reff Truewood and his son representing the Mages; and Kinool Goldsinger and his son of the Enchanters.&quot;<br>
<br>
Grinning as handsomely as he can, Ward takes up the hand of his friend as he slides out of the booth, kisses her hand, saying out loud, &quot;And where shall we dance the night away, my beautiful lady,&quot;......... while inside he is thinking &quot;Well I'm not the true heir.....so now what do I do?...... Shall I convince one of the real heirs to help me get to that book and give away that I'm not really the child of Prince Nobleheart, or do I trick his secret daughter into helping me get to that book.&quot;<br>
<br>
He chuckles at a picture in his head of Saffryn Trueshot glaring at him when he asks her to help him.... a chuckle that Seleni assumes is for her as they go off into the night together.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
